ENTRY            M0589   20260120   20260226   20260226       M143
SUBENT        M0589001   20260120   20260226   20260226       M143
BIB                 13         58
TITLE      Photon scattering from 12C and 4He nuclei near the
            DELTA (1232) resonance.
AUTHOR     (R.Igarashi,J.C.Bergstrom,H.S.Caplan,K.G.E.Doss,
            E.L.Hallin,D.M.Skopik,D.Delli Carpini,E.C.Booth,
            E.K.Mcintyre,J.P.Miller,M.A.Lucas,B.E.Macgibbon,
            A.M.Nathan,D.Wells)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,52,755,1995)
INSTITUTE  (1CANSAS,1USAUI,1USABST)
FACILITY   (LINAC,1CANSAS) 300 MeV linac at Saskatchevan
            Accelerator Laboratory pulse stretcher ring.
INC-SOURCE (BRST)
METHOD     (EXTB,SITA)
DETECTOR   (NAICR) The Boston University large NaI(Tl) gamma
            spectrometer with 1.7 % resolution which is a
            26.7 cm diameter cylindrical core of NaI surrounded
            by 10.8 cm thick quadrant crystals of NaI.
SAMPLE     Two carbon targets were used, one 3.98 g/cm2 thick,
            the other 1.6 g/cm2.
           No information about helium target.
ANALYSIS   Differential cross sections for photon scattering have
            been measured with a high resolution gamma ray
            spectrometer that ensured total rejection of neutral
            pion background and good separation of elastic from
            inelastic events.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-S) Statistical errors.
           (ERR-1) Systematic errors the major sources of which
            were the quantameter calibration and the NaI energy
            calibration.
COMMENT    Angular distributions for photon scattering from 12C
            and 4He have been measured using continuous wave
            bremsstrahlung from the Saskatchevan Accelerator
            Laboratory pulse stretcher ring. Data for carbon were
            taken at 158.8, 195.2, 197.2, 247.2, and 290.2 MeV
            end-point energies, and for helium were taken at
            an end-point energy of 158.8 MeV. A large NaI(Tl)
            gamma ray spectrometer with 1.7% resolution was
            used to detect scattered photons at laboratory
            scattering angles, ranging from 20 to 150 degree.
            The excellent energy resolution of the NaI detector
            allowed a separation of elastic from inelastic
            photon scattering for the first time at these
            energies. The angular distributions for elastic
            scattering are in only fair agreement with delta-hole
            theory and theory based on the optical theorem at
            forward angles, and completely disagree with theory
            at backward angles. Measured cross sections for
            inelastic scattering leading to the 4.43 MeV state
            in carbon are small compared to the elastic
            scattering at forward angles, but are dominant at
            backward angles. This experiment is the first to
            separate elastic from inelastic photon scattering
            at these energies.
HISTORY    (19990326C) Data were compiled at the USA BNL NNDC by
           V.Varlamov.
           (20111117A) Corrected by V.Varlamov: AUTHOR, TITLE,
            lowercase.
           (20260120A) Corrected by VV and SD: DATA, ANALYSIS,
            COMMON, STATUS,
ENDBIB              58
